SIMPLE: inculcate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inculcate
<hw>In*cul"cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inculcated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inculcating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>inculcatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>inculcare</ets> to tread on; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in, on + <ets>calcare</ets> to tread, fr. <ets>calx</ets>
the heel; perh. akin to E. <ets>heel</ets>. Cf. 2d <er>Calk</er>,
<er>Heel</er>.]</ety> <def>To teach and impress by frequent repetitions
or admonitions; to urge on the mind; <as>as, Christ <ex>inculcates</ex>
on his followers humility</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The most obvious and necessary duties of life they have not yet
had authority enough to enforce and <qex>inculcate</qex> upon men's
minds.</q> <rj><qau>S. Clarke.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To instill; infuse; implant; engraft;
impress.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inculcation</ent>⟦br⟧
